The '''Curaçao national football team''' ({{langx|nl|Curaçaos voetbalelftal}}; {{langx|pap|selekshon di futbòl Kòrsou}}) represents [[Curaçao]] in men's international [[association football|football]], it is controlled by the [[Curaçao Football Federation|Federashon Futbòl Kòrsou]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.elsalvador.com/deportes/futbol/372358/curazao-pierde-a-su-capitan-para-el-juego-ante-la-selecta/| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170714164913/http://www.elsalvador.com/deportes/futbol/372358/curazao-pierde-a-su-capitan-para-el-juego-ante-la-selecta| archive-date = 2017-07-14| title = Curazao pierde a su capitán para el juego ante la Selecta {{!}} elsalvador.com}}</ref>

Following a constitutional change that allowed its predecessor, the [[Curaçao and Dependencies|Colony of Curaçao and Dependencies]], to become a unified [[constituent state|constituent country]] consisting of several island territories as the [[Netherlands Antilles]] and its dissolution in 2010, Curaçao has played under a new constitutional status as a separate constituent country since 2011.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gg1hDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA121 |title=Football and the Boundaries of History: Critical Studies in Soccer |editor=Elsey, Brenda |editor2=Pugliese, Stanislao G. |year=2017 |page=121 |isbn=978-1-349-95006-5 |publisher= Springer |access-date=25 June 2019}}</ref>

Both [[FIFA]] and [[CONCACAF]] recognize the Curaçao national team as the direct successor of the dependant [[Territory of Curaçao national football team|Territory of Curaçao]] (1921–1958) and the [[Netherlands Antilles national football team|Netherlands Antilles]] (1958–2010).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20190626032129/https://www.fifa.com/associations/association/cuw/about Curaçao] at [[FIFA]] official website</ref><ref>[https://www.concacaf.com/en/member-association/curacao Curaçao] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210309013123/https://www.concacaf.com/en/member-association/curacao |date=9 March 2021 }} at [[CONCACAF]] official website</ref><ref>[https://www.rsssf.org/tablesc/curacaochamp.html Curaçao — List of Champions]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230203071708/https://www.rsssf.org/tablesc/curacaochamp.html|date=3 February 2023}}. [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]].</ref>

In November 2025, they topped their qualifying group and qualified for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], becoming the smallest nation by both population and area to qualify for the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |date=19 November 2025 |title=Population of... 156,000: Caribbean minnows break wild record to secure WC spot — Wrap |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/wild-scenes-as-27year-wc-drought-ends-with-stunning-goals-and-red-card-drama-wrap/news-story/a41294afec3801b915e75c9b1784a852 |access-date=19 November 2025 |work=Fox Sports Australia}}</ref> Curaçao became the first non-sovereign national team from the Americas to qualify for the FIFA World Cup, and the seventh overall, after England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland (which are constituent countries of the United Kingdom and not independent countries) the Netherlands (a constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands), and the [[Indonesia national football team|Dutch East Indies]], a Dutch colony that competed in the [[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938 tournament]].

==History==
{{Further|Territory of Curaçao national football team|Netherlands Antilles national football team}}

The first national football team to bear the name Curaçao was the [[Territory of Curaçao national football team]], which made its debut in 1924 in an away match against neighboring [[Aruba national football team|Aruba]], a match which the Territory of Curaçao won four to nil.

In December 1954, the territory of Curaçao became the [[Netherlands Antilles]], and following a constitutional change the Netherlands Antilles were designated a country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, which included the islands of [[Aruba]], [[Bonaire]], [[Saba (island)|Saba]], [[Sint Eustatius]] and [[Sint Maarten]]. The name of the Curaçao team changed to [[Netherlands Antilles national football team|Netherlands Antilles national team]], representing all six islands.

In 1986, Aruba became a country within the Kingdom in its own right, with its own [[Aruba national football team|Aruba national team]] and subsequently Aruban players no longer represented the Netherlands Antilles.

On 10 October 2010, the Netherlands Antilles were dissolved, and Curaçao and [[Sint Maarten national football team|Sint Maarten]] became countries in their own right, while Bonaire, Saba and Sint Eustatius became part of the Netherlands proper. Although not a [[sovereignty|sovereign state]], Curaçao (the largest island territory in the Netherlands Antilles) appeared on the FIFA member list in March 2011, as successor of the [[Netherlands Antilles national football team|Netherlands Antilles]].

As well as taking on the [[Netherlands Antilles]]' FIFA membership, [[Curaçao]] was recognised as the direct successor of the former (similarly to how [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] is regarded the direct successor of [[Yugoslavia national football team|Yugoslavia]], and [[Russia national football team|Russia]] for the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]]), and took on its historical records and FIFA ranking.

They played their first match as the newly formed Curaçao national team on 20 August 2011 against [[Dominican Republic national football team|Dominican Republic]] at the [[Estadio Panamericano, San Cristóbal|Estadio Panamericano]], with the match ending in a 1–0 loss for Curaçao.

During the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|CONCACAF Qualification for the 2018 FIFA World Cup]], Curaçao achieved a major feat when they defeated Cuba 1–1 with the [[away goals rule]].

=== CONCACAF Gold Cup debut ===
After a strong qualification campaign, Curaçao defeated host [[Martinique national football team|Martinique]] in the semi-finals of the [[2017 Caribbean Cup|2017]] edition of the [[Caribbean Cup]] with the score of 2–1. They met defending champions and six-time winners, [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]]. Curaçao won their first ever Caribbean Cup by defeating Jamaica, again with the scoreline of 2–1 which see Curaçao  qualified to their first ever [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. Curaçao was then drawn in Group C in the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] alongside Jamaica, [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] but unfortunately, lost all of their group stage matches.

In the next edition of the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], Curaçao was then drawn in Group C alongside El Salvador, Jamaica and [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]]. On 21 June 2019, Curaçao got their first win in the CONCACAF Gold Cup where [[Leandro Bacuna]] scored in a 1–0 win over Honduras. With a much needed win to qualified to the next round, [[Juriën Gaari]] scored a stoppage time goal against Jamaica in the last group stage fixtures which saw Curaçao finishing as runners-up in the group stage thus qualifying to the knockout stage. In the quarter-finals, Curaçao then bowed out from the tournament after losing to [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]].

=== FIFA World Cup debut ===
In November 2025, during the [[2026_FIFA_World_Cup_qualification_–_CONCACAF_third_round#Group_B|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]], Curaçao drew 0–0 against Jamaica, making Curaçao the smallest nation by both population and area (only five weeks after [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]] had broken the area record) ever to qualify for the [[FIFA World Cup]] in history.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Unwin |first1=Will |title='An impossibility made possible': how tiny Curaçao made World Cup history |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/nov/19/curacao-fifa-world-cup-qualification-dick-advocaat |website=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=23 November 2025 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20251123233308/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/nov/19/curacao-fifa-world-cup-qualification-dick-advocaat |archive-date=23 November 2025 |date=19 November 2025}}</ref> On 23 February 2026, manager [[Dick Advocaat]] would resign as Curaçao's manager due to personal reasons regarding the health of his daughter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vi.nl/nieuws/cura-ao-zonder-advocaat-naar-wk-rutten-neemt-taken-over |title=Curaçao zonder Advocaat naar WK, Rutten neemt taken over |trans-title=Curaçao without Advocaat to the World Cup, Rutten takes over |language=Dutch |date=23 February 2026 |access-date=23 February 2026}}</ref> Subsequently, [[Fred Rutten]] was appointed as head coach ahead of the World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-au/football/fifa-world-cup-2026/articles/advocaat-leaves-curacao-role-after-overseeing-historic-world-cup-qualification-2026-02-23 |title=Advocaat leaves Curacao role after overseeing historic World Cup qualification |publisher=beIN SPORTS |date=23 February 2026 }}</ref> On May 11, after his daughter's health improved, Advocaat returned to the national team. This was also due to disagreements between the national team's players and Advocaat's successor [[Fred Rutten]] as well as pressure from the national team's main sponsor, Dutch airline company Corendon.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ad.nl/voetbal/dick-advocaat-toch-met-curacao-naar-het-wk-fred-rutten-trekt-zich-terug~a63ed30f8/ |title=Dick Advocaat toch met Curaçao naar het WK, Fred Rutten trekt zich terug |trans-title=Dick Advocaat will go to the World Cup with Curaçao after all, Fred Rutten resigns |publisher=[[Algemeen Dagblad|AD]] |date=May 11, 2026}}</ref> With his return, Advocaat will become the oldest manager in history to coach a team the during the FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{cite web |title=Advocaat to become oldest coach at World Cup after Curacao qualification |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/advocaat-become-oldest-coach-world-cup-after-curacao-qualification-2025-11-19/ |website=[[Reuters]] |access-date=23 November 2025 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20251123233506/https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/advocaat-become-oldest-coach-world-cup-after-curacao-qualification-2025-11-19/ |archive-date=23 November 2025 |location=[[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]] |date=19 November 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cryer |first1=Andy |title=Curacao become smallest nation to qualify for World Cup |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c14p3dmdld1o |website=[[BBC Sport]] |access-date=23 November 2025 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20251123233626/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c14p3dmdld1o |archive-date=23 November 2025 |date=19 November 2025}}</ref> 

